## PROJECT IDENTITY
This is a guided Sanatan Dharma / Hinduism learning app.
- Sanskrit → Hindi + English, offline-first
- Target: Beginners, Diaspora, Curious Hindus, Non-Hindus globally
- No fixed deadline — engineer for quality, not speed

## ARCHITECTURE: STRICT CLEAN ARCHITECTURE
MANDATORY. Never violate layer boundaries.

Layer 1 — domain/ (pure Dart, ZERO Flutter imports allowed)
  - entities/     → Immutable domain objects (freezed)
  - repositories/ → Abstract interfaces only
  - usecases/     → Single-responsibility use case classes

Layer 2 — data/ (implements domain interfaces)
  - datasources/local/  → Drift DAOs
  - datasources/remote/ → API clients (Dio)
  - models/             → DTOs with fromJson/toJson (freezed + json_serializable)
  - repositories/       → Concrete implementations of domain interfaces

Layer 3 — presentation/ (Flutter UI)
  - features/[name]/
      - pages/      → Screens (ConsumerWidget, ConsumerStatefulWidget only)
      - widgets/    → Reusable widgets for this feature
      - providers/  → Riverpod providers and notifiers
  - shared/widgets/ → App-wide reusable widgets
  - theme/          → AppTheme, AppColors, AppTypography, AppSpacing

core/ — Shared utilities, no business logic
  - constants/  → AppConstants, AppStrings
  - errors/     → Failure classes, AppException
  - extensions/ → Dart extension methods
  - utils/      → Pure helper functions

## STATE MANAGEMENT: RIVERPOD 2.x (riverpod_generator)
ALWAYS use code generation (@riverpod annotation).

Rules:
- AsyncNotifier for async data with loading/error/data states
- Notifier for synchronous complex state
- AutoDisposeNotifier for screen-scoped state (default for most features)
- Notifier (non-dispose) ONLY for truly global state: AudioPlayerNotifier, UserProgressNotifier
- StreamProvider for reactive Drift DB .watch() streams
- Provider (plain) for computed/derived values and dependency injection
- NEVER use StateProvider for complex state — use Notifier
- NEVER use StateNotifierProvider — deprecated in Riverpod 2.x

Provider naming:
- @riverpod → generates [name]Provider
- Keep provider names descriptive: verseOfTheDayProvider, not votdProvider
- Notifier class: [FeatureName]Notifier
- Provider family: [name]Provider (use .family modifier)

Accessing providers:
- ref.watch() in build() — ALWAYS
- ref.read() in callbacks/handlers — ONLY
- ref.listen() for side effects (navigation, snackbars)
- NEVER use ref.read() in build() — silent bug

## DATABASE: DRIFT 2.x (SQLite)
ALL DB access goes through domain repository interfaces. Never call DAO from UI.

Rules:
- Table names: snake_case plural (verses, learning_modules, user_progress_records)
- Use @DriftDatabase for the main AppDatabase class
- DAOs annotated with @DriftAccessor
- Use .watch() streams for reactive UI — never poll
- Run DB in background isolate for bulk operations (compute or Drift isolate)
- For scripture content: bundle pre-populated .db in assets/db/
  Copy to documents dir on first launch, open with Drift
- Use Drift migrations (stepByStep) for schema changes — never drop-recreate

## TESTING: TDD-ISH (tests alongside implementation)
Test file location: mirrors source tree under test/
e.g. lib/domain/usecases/get_verse_usecase.dart
→  test/domain/usecases/get_verse_usecase_test.dart

Testing stack:
- flutter_test (standard)
- mocktail (NOT mockito) for mocking
- riverpod testing: ProviderContainer for notifier tests

MANDATORY test coverage:
1. All use cases (unit test, mock repositories)
2. All repository implementations (unit test, mock data sources)
3. All Notifiers with meaningful state transitions
4. Critical widgets (verse reader, learning path card) — widget tests

Test structure: Arrange / Act / Assert pattern, always with comments:
```dart
test('should return verse when repository succeeds', () async {
  // Arrange
  when(() => mockRepo.getVerse(any())).thenAnswer((_) async => testVerse);
  
  // Act
  final result = await useCase.execute(GetVerseParams(verseId: 'BG1.1'));
  
  // Assert
  expect(result, isA<Right<Failure, Verse>>());
});
```

## DART/FLUTTER CODE RULES
- Dart SDK: >=3.0.0 (use Dart 3 features: sealed classes, switch expressions, patterns)
- Null safety: mandatory, no ! operator unless you can prove non-null
- const: use everywhere possible (const constructors, const widgets)
- Immutability: all entities/models must be immutable (use freezed)
- Named params: all functions with 2+ parameters must use named parameters
- No dynamic: never use dynamic type unless absolutely required (JSON deserialization only)
- switch expressions over if-else chains for exhaustive matching
- Extension methods over utility classes for cleaner APIs
- Max function body: 40 lines. If longer, extract.
- Max file: 300 lines. If longer, split.
- No magic numbers: extract to AppConstants or local const
- No hardcoded strings in widgets: use AppStrings constants
- BuildContext safety: ALWAYS check mounted before using context after await

## ERROR HANDLING
Use Either<Failure, T> pattern (fpdart package) in repository and use case layers.
Define specific Failure subclasses in core/errors/failures.dart:
```dart
sealed class Failure {
  final String message;
  const Failure(this.message);
}
class DatabaseFailure extends Failure { ... }
class NetworkFailure extends Failure { ... }
class CacheFailure extends Failure { ... }
```

NEVER throw raw exceptions from repository layer upward.
Map all exceptions to Failure types in repository implementations.

## SANSKRIT / DEVANAGARI RULES
- Font: TiroDevanagari (bundled asset) for Sanskrit shlokas
- Font: NotoSansDevanagari (bundled asset) for Hindi UI text
- Minimum fontSize: 18 for any Sanskrit text — never smaller
- lineHeight: 1.8 minimum for Sanskrit shloka display blocks
- Store Sanskrit text as UTF-8 Devanagari Unicode in DB (U+0900–U+097F)
- IAST transliteration: computed on-the-fly from stored Devanagari — not stored separately
- Always provide font scaling (respect system textScaleFactor)
- Test Sanskrit rendering on: Pixel 3a (API 28), Samsung A-series (API 30)

## AD PLACEMENT — INVIOLABLE RULES
ALLOWED: app open screens, between learning modules, in article/festival feed
NEVER PLACE ADS IN:
  - Scripture reader screen (any verse/shloka display)
  - Mantra audio player
  - Puja vidhi step-by-step screens
  - Any active meditation/practice screen
If in doubt: no ad. The sacred content is the product — never let ads touch it.

## THEME & DESIGN SYSTEM
ALL colors from AppColors — never hardcode hex in widgets
ALL text styles from AppTypography — never hardcode font in widgets
ALL spacing from AppSpacing (use 4pt grid: 4, 8, 12, 16, 24, 32, 48, 64)
Support both light and dark themes from day 1
Colors defined in AppColors:
  saffron: #FF9933 (primary brand, CTAs)
  deepRed: #8B0000 (headers, important text)
  cream: #FFF8E7 (primary background light)
  gold: #FFD700 (decorative, badges)
  forestGreen: #1B5E20 (completion, streaks)
  charcoal: #1A1A1A (body text)

## NAVIGATION: go_router
Define ALL routes in a single AppRouter class in core/router/
Use GoRoute with typed params — never pass complex objects through routes
Named routes with AppRoutes constants class
Handle deep links for verse sharing (sanatan://verse/BG1.1)
Guards for authenticated routes using redirect

## LOGGING
Use the logger package — NEVER use print() or debugPrint() in production code
Logger instance: AppLogger.instance (singleton in core/)
Log levels: verbose (dev only), debug, info, warning, error
Remove verbose/debug in release builds

## DEPENDENCY INJECTION
Use Riverpod providers for DI — no get_it or injectable needed
Register data sources and repositories as providers in data/providers/
Domain use cases get repo via constructor injection (passed by provider)

## WHAT CURSOR MUST NEVER DO
- Never put business logic in a widget or page
- Never access Drift DAO directly from a widget or provider
- Never use BuildContext across async gaps without mounted check
- Never generate God objects — single responsibility always
- Never use setState for app state — only for local animation state
- Never commit TODO comments in generated code
- Never hardcode colors, strings, or spacing in widgets
- Never use print() — use AppLogger
- Never import dart:io or dart:html in domain or presentation layers
- Never generate a "working" implementation that skips error handling
- Never use late keyword unless truly necessary and well-commented why
- Never skip const on constructors that can be const
- Never generate widget tests that only test rendering — test behavior

## CODE GENERATION
Run after any change to annotated files:
  flutter pub run build_runner build --delete-conflicting-outputs
Files ending in .g.dart and .freezed.dart are generated — never edit manually

## BEFORE GENERATING ANY FILE, CHECK:
1. Does this belong in domain, data, or presentation layer?
2. Is there an existing abstraction I should implement rather than create new?
3. Will this be testable without Flutter? (domain/data: yes always)
4. Am I creating a new constant instead of using AppConstants?
5. Am I handling all three states: loading, error, success?
